      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the bara dough",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the {{plain-flour}}, {{yeast-dried}}, {{turmeric}}, {{cumin-ground}}, {{sea-salt-fine}}, and {{caster-sugar}} in a bowl. Add 180 ml of warm water and mix to a soft, sticky dough. Knead for 5 minutes, the dough should be softer than bread dough. Cover and rest for 30 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the channa",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a pan over medium heat. Add the {{onion}} and cook for 5 minutes until softened. Add the {{garlic}}, {{ginger-root}}, {{curry-powder}}, and {{cumin-ground}} and cook for 2 minutes. Add the {{scotch-bonnet}} and the {{chickpeas}}. Pour in 200 ml of water and stir. Simmer for 15 minutes until the sauce has thickened and the chickpeas are very well seasoned. Add the {{coriander}} and {{sea-salt-fine}}. The channa should be moist but not soupy. Keep warm.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the bara",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Divide the bara dough into 24 pieces (2 per serving). Wet your hands with oil and press each piece into a thin round about 10 cm across, do not use a rolling pin, use your fingers and palms. Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} to 170°C in a wide pan. Fry each bara for about 30 seconds per side until lightly golden and puffed. They cook very fast. Drain on kitchen paper. To serve, stack two bara and spoon on the channa. Add mango chutney, pepper sauce, and coriander chutney to taste.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Rest the dough for the full 30 minutes. Bara should only take 30 seconds per side, more than this and they become tough",
              "cause": "Dough not rested or fried too long",
              "symptom": "Bara too tough and chewy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Press the bara as thin as possible, no more than 3 mm. If the oil is below 165°C, the bara will absorb oil and not puff",
              "cause": "Dough too thick or oil not hot enough",
              "symptom": "Bara not puffing"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Add water a tablespoon at a time. The channa should be moist enough to scoop without being wet",
              "cause": "Too little water or cooked too long",
              "symptom": "Channa too dry"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Doubles is the national street food of Trinidad. More Trinidadians eat it for breakfast than any other single food. Vendors set up before dawn and often sell out by 9 am. The transaction is fast: you say 'slight, medium, or heavy' for the pepper sauce, pay, and you are done in under a minute. In Britain, doubles appears at Trinidadian restaurants and food events. The same basic structure applies, but the full range of traditional chutneys is rarely available.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
